```

### What changed / why it’s still equivalent
| Python | TypeScript |
|--------|------------|
| `def greet(*names):` | `function greet(...names: string[])` – the rest‑parameter syntax is the direct counterpart. |
| `print('Hello ', end='')` | `process.stdout.write('Hello ')` – writes without a newline, matching the Python `end=''`. |
| `while len(names) > i:` + `print(names[i], end=', ')` | `for (const name of names) { process.stdout.write(`${name}, `); }` – iterates over the array and appends `, ` after each element. |
| No explicit newline at the end of the loop | Added `process.stdout.write('\n')` only to keep the console tidy; the core output (the trailing comma after the last name) is identical. |

If you prefer a more “string‑builder” style, you could also accumulate the whole message in a variable and then `console.log` it, but the above keeps the exact step‑by‑step behaviour of the original Python code.

